---
title: Faster-Than-Takeout Pork Wonton Soup with Bok Choy, Cabbage, Carrots & Wonton Strips
description: Enjoy the savory flavors of homemade wonton soup with our quick and clever shortcut! This "deconstructed" version stars savory ground pork simmered in a umami-rich broth. Tender wonton wrappers cook in a flash along with bok choy and cabbage. Serve with a shower of scallion greens and crunchy wonton strips for a meal that's even better than take-out!
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/678564f2aac2798c14863866-22702be9.jpeg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/678564f2aac2798c14863866-en-US.pdf
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/faster-than-takeout-pork-wonton-soup-678564f2aac2798c14863866
servings: 2
time required: 25 minutes
cuisine: East Asia
author: Sara Heilman
course: main course
nutrition:
  calories: 690 kcal
  fat: 37 g
  saturated fat: 10 g
  carbohydrates: 53 g
  sugar: 8 g
  protein: 32 g
  fiber: 3 g
  sodium: 2740 mg
---

Wash and dry produce.

Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}(trimmed and sliced), separating whites from greens. Peel and mince or grate @garlic{3%cloves}(minced). Peel and mince or grate @ginger{1%thumb}(minced).

Remove half the @wonton wrappers{24%piece} from package. TIP: Extra wonton wrappers freeze well for up to three months! Simply wrap tightly in plastic wrap and store in a freezer-friendly plastic bag.

Stack wonton wrappers; cut diagonally into quarters to create small triangles. Separate wonton triangles into a pile and cover with a clean #kitchen towel{}.

Heat @sesame oil{1%tablespoon} in a large #pot{} over medium-high heat. Add @ground pork{10%ounce}; season with half the @soy sauce{2%tablespoon} (you'll use the rest in the next step), @sugar{1/2%tsp}, and @pepper{}. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until pork begins to brown, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add scallion whites, garlic, ginger, and half the @shredded carrots{4%ounce}. Stir to combine. Cook, stirring occasionally, until carrots begin to soften and pork is cooked through, ~{3-4%minutes} more.

Add @water{5%cups}, @pork ramen stock concentrate{2}, @mushroom stock concentrate{1}, and remaining soy sauce to pot with pork and veggies. Stir to combine. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat to medium.

Carefully add wonton triangles to pot a small handful at a time. (TIP: Stirring the soup constantly as you add the wonton triangles will prevent the pieces from sticking together—but it's OK if a few do!) Cook, stirring occasionally, until wonton triangles are tender, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add @bok choy and napa cabbage{4%ounce} to pot; stir to combine. Remove from heat. Taste and season with @salt{} and pepper.

Divide soup between #bowls{}. Garnish with scallion greens and @wonton strips{1}. Serve.

> If you like things spicy, serve with Sriracha or your favorite hot sauce!

> Ground Meat is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.